{
 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Phase 4: Flight Delay Prediction Modeling (Simplified \u2014 Course Style)\n",
    "\n",
    "**Course:** COMP4381 Data Science\n",
    "\n",
    "This is a simplified version of the Phase 4 notebook. It keeps the same goal a **two-stage system**\n",
    "that predicts flight delay but the code now only uses the methods we actually covered in class:\n",
    "\n",
    "- `train_test_split` (random split, like every example in the slides)\n",
    "- `ColumnTransformer` + `SimpleImputer` + `StandardScaler` + `OneHotEncoder`\n",
    "- `LinearRegression` and `LogisticRegression`\n",
    "- The evaluation metrics from the slides: MAE, MSE, RMSE, R\u00b2 (regression) and Accuracy,\n",
    "  Precision, Recall, F1, Confusion Matrix (classification)\n",
    "- Comparing train vs test metrics to check overfitting / underfitting\n",
    "\n",
    "**Removed compared to the old version** (because we never covered these in class):\n",
    "lag/rolling features, chronological (date-based) splitting, ROC/AUC, `class_weight=\"balanced\"`,\n",
    "and the long leakage-assertion checks. Leakage is still handled the simple way we were taught:\n",
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 1. Imports"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "\n",
    "from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split\n",
    "from sklearn.pipeline import make_pipeline\n",
    "from sklearn.compose import ColumnTransformer\n",
    "from sklearn.impute import SimpleImputer\n",
    "from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler, OneHotEncoder\n",
    "from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression, LogisticRegression\n",
    "from sklearn.metrics import (\n",
    "    mean_absolute_error, mean_squared_error, r2_score,\n",
    "    accuracy_score, precision_score, recall_score, f1_score,\n",
    "    classification_report, ConfusionMatrixDisplay,\n",
    ")\n",
    "from sklearn import set_config\n",
    "\n",
    "set_config(transform_output='pandas')",
    "pd.set_option(\"display.max_columns\", None)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 2. Load the data"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# TODO: update this path to wherever your Phase 3 cleaned CSV actually is\n",
    "DATA_PATH = \"phase3_airport_day_clean.csv\"\n",
    "\n",
    "df = pd.read_csv(DATA_PATH)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"Dataset shape: {df.shape}\")\n",
    "df.head()\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 3. Quick look at the data (basic EDA)\n",
    "\n",
    "Same checks we always did before modeling: missing values and duplicate rows."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "print(\"Missing values per column:\")\n",
    "print(df.isnull().sum())\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"\\nDuplicate rows:\", df.duplicated().sum())\n",
    "\n",
    "# Drop duplicate rows if any (same as the model-validation slide)\n",
    "df = df.drop_duplicates()\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 4. Drop leakage columns\n",
    "\n",
    "**Data leakage** = using information that the model would not actually have *before* making a\n",
    "prediction. The columns below describe the **same-day arrival outcome**, so they basically give\n",
    "away the answer. We drop them the simple way we were taught: just remove the columns.\n",
    "\n",
    "We also drop `Date` itself we already have `year`, `month`, `weekday`, `is_weekend`, and\n",
    "`season` as separate columns, so the raw date string isn't needed as a feature."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "leakage_cols = [\n",
    "    \"target_delay_category\",\n",
    "    \"arr_delay_min\",\n",
    "    \"Avg Arrival Schedule Delay\",\n",
    "    \"Arrival Punctuality %\",\n",
    "    \"arr_punctuality_pct\",\n",
    "    \"Date\",\n",
    "]\n",
    "\n",
    "# Only drop the ones that actually exist in this dataset\n",
    "leakage_cols = [c for c in leakage_cols if c in df.columns]\n",
    "df = df.drop(columns=leakage_cols)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Dropped columns:\", leakage_cols)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 5. Define features (X) and the two targets (y)\n",
    "\n",
    "- `y_class` Stage 1 target: was the airport-day delayed 15+ minutes? (0/1, classification)\n",
    "- `y_reg`  Stage 2 target: how many delay minutes? (continuous, regression)\n",
    "\n",
    "Everything else becomes our feature matrix `X`, exactly like the `medical_data.csv` example\n",
    "from class (`X = df.drop(columns='Additional_charges')`)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "y_class = df[\"target_delayed_15\"]\n",
    "y_reg   = df[\"target_delay_minutes\"]\n",
    "\n",
    "X = df.drop(columns=[\"target_delayed_15\", \"target_delay_minutes\"])\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Feature matrix shape:\", X.shape)\n",
    "X.head()\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 6. Train / test split\n",
    "\n",
    "A plain random 80/20 split with `random_state` set so the results are reproducible \u2014 the same\n",
    "kind of split used in every example in the slides (no need for anything fancier)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "X_train, X_test, y_class_train, y_class_test, y_reg_train, y_reg_test = train_test_split(\n",
    "    X, y_class, y_reg, test_size=0.2, random_state=42\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Train rows:\", X_train.shape[0])\n",
    "print(\"Test rows: \", X_test.shape[0])\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 7. Preprocessing pipeline\n",
    "\n",
    "Same recipe as the Linear Regression / Logistic Regression examples in class:\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Numeric columns:** fill missing values with the median, then `StandardScaler`\n",
    "- **Categorical columns:** fill missing values with the most frequent value, then `OneHotEncoder`\n",
    "\n",
    "We build this preprocessor once and reuse it for both Stage 1 and Stage 2."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "num_cols = X_train.select_dtypes(\"number\").columns\n",
    "cat_cols = X_train.select_dtypes(\"object\").columns\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Numeric columns:\", list(num_cols))\n",
    "print(\"Categorical columns:\", list(cat_cols))\n",
    "\n",
    "# Numeric pipeline\n",
    "impute_median = SimpleImputer(strategy=\"median\")\n",
    "scaler = StandardScaler()\n",
    "num_pipe = make_pipeline(impute_median, scaler)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Categorical pipeline\n",
    "impute_mode = SimpleImputer(strategy=\"most_frequent\")\n",
    "ohe = OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown=\"ignore\")\n",
    "cat_pipe = make_pipeline(impute_mode, ohe)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Combine into one ColumnTransformer (reused for both stages)\n",
    "preprocessor = ColumnTransformer([\n",
    "    (\"numeric\", num_pipe, num_cols),\n",
    "    (\"categorical\", cat_pipe, cat_cols),\n",
    "], remainder=\"drop\", verbose_feature_names_out=False)\n",
    "\n",
    "preprocessor\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "# Stage 1: Logistic Regression \u2014 Will the airport-day be delayed?\n",
    "\n",
    "Logistic Regression is the classification model we used in class. It uses the **sigmoid\n",
    "function** to turn a linear combination of the features into a probability between 0 and 1.\n",
    "If that probability is above 0.5, the model predicts class 1 (delayed); otherwise class 0\n",
    "(on-time)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 8. Fit the Logistic Regression model"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "clf_model = LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000)\n",
    "clf_pipeline = make_pipeline(preprocessor, clf_model)\n",
    "\n",
    "clf_pipeline.fit(X_train, y_class_train)\n",
    "\n",
    "clf_test_pred = clf_pipeline.predict(X_test)\n",
    "print(\"Logistic Regression trained.\")\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 9. Look at the model parameters\n",
    "\n",
    "Same as in class: each coefficient tells us, after scaling, how a one-standard-deviation\n",
    "increase in that feature changes the **log-odds** of being delayed (positive = pushes toward\n",
    "delayed, negative = pushes toward on-time)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "feature_names = clf_pipeline.named_steps[\"columntransformer\"].get_feature_names_out()\n",
    "b_0 = clf_model.intercept_[0].round(2)\n",
    "b_i = clf_model.coef_[0].round(2)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"intercept (bias): {b_0}\")\n",
    "for name, weight in zip(feature_names, b_i):\n",
    "    print(f\"{name:30s} weight = {weight:+.2f}\")\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 10. Evaluate Stage 1 on the test set\n",
    "\n",
    "The same four metrics from class: Accuracy, Precision, Recall, F1-score, plus the confusion\n",
    "matrix and the full classification report."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "accuracy  = accuracy_score(y_class_test, clf_test_pred)\n",
    "precision = precision_score(y_class_test, clf_test_pred)\n",
    "recall    = recall_score(y_class_test, clf_test_pred)\n",
    "f1        = f1_score(y_class_test, clf_test_pred)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"Accuracy:  {accuracy:.3f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Precision: {precision:.3f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Recall:    {recall:.3f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"F1-score:  {f1:.3f}\")\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "ConfusionMatrixDisplay.from_predictions(y_class_test, clf_test_pred);\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "print(classification_report(y_class_test, clf_test_pred, target_names=[\"On-time\", \"Delayed\"]))\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 11. Overfit / underfit check \u2014 Stage 1\n",
    "\n",
    "Same approach as the \"students pass/not pass\" example from class: evaluate the model on the\n",
    "**training** data too, then compare.\n",
    "\n",
    "- Train and test scores close together and both acceptable -> good model\n",
    "- Train much higher than test -> overfitting\n",
    "- Both low -> underfitting"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "clf_train_pred = clf_pipeline.predict(X_train)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Classification report: Training data\")\n",
    "print(classification_report(y_class_train, clf_train_pred, target_names=[\"On-time\", \"Delayed\"]))\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Classification report: Test data\")\n",
    "print(classification_report(y_class_test, clf_test_pred, target_names=[\"On-time\", \"Delayed\"]))\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**My interpretation:** *(fill this in after running the cells above on your real data \u2014 compare\n",
    "the train vs test accuracy / F1 and say whether you see overfitting, underfitting, or neither.)*"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "# Stage 2: Linear Regression \u2014 How many delay minutes?\n",
    "\n",
    "Linear Regression is the regression model from class. It predicts a **continuous** number\n",
    "(delay minutes) using the equation:\n",
    "\n",
    "**\u0177 = \u03b2\u2080 + \u03b2\u2081x\u2081 + \u03b2\u2082x\u2082 + ... + \u03b2\u2099x\u2099**"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 12. Fit the Linear Regression model"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "reg_model = LinearRegression()\n",
    "reg_pipeline = make_pipeline(preprocessor, reg_model)\n",
    "\n",
    "reg_pipeline.fit(X_train, y_reg_train)\n",
    "\n",
    "reg_test_pred = reg_pipeline.predict(X_test)\n",
    "print(\"Linear Regression trained.\")\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 13. Look at the model parameters"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "feature_names_reg = reg_pipeline.named_steps[\"columntransformer\"].get_feature_names_out()\n",
    "b_0_reg = reg_model.intercept_.round(2)\n",
    "b_i_reg = reg_model.coef_.round(2)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"intercept (bias): {b_0_reg}\")\n",
    "for name, weight in zip(feature_names_reg, b_i_reg):\n",
    "    print(f\"{name:30s} weight = {weight:+.2f}\")\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 14. Evaluate Stage 2 on the test set\n",
    "\n",
    "The four regression metrics from class, using the same helper-function style we used in\n",
    "the lecture (so we can reuse it for train vs test)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def regression_metrics(y_true, y_pred, label=\"\"):\n",
    "    mae  = mean_absolute_error(y_true, y_pred)\n",
    "    mse  = mean_squared_error(y_true, y_pred)\n",
    "    rmse = mse ** 0.5\n",
    "    r2   = r2_score(y_true, y_pred)\n",
    "\n",
    "    print(\"-\" * 50)\n",
    "    print(f\"Regression Metrics: {label}\")\n",
    "    print(\"-\" * 50)\n",
    "    print(f\"- MAE  = {mae:,.3f}\")\n",
    "    print(f\"- MSE  = {mse:,.3f}\")\n",
    "    print(f\"- RMSE = {rmse:,.3f}\")\n",
    "    print(f\"- R^2  = {r2:,.3f}\")\n",
    "\n",
    "regression_metrics(y_reg_test, reg_test_pred, label=\"Test Data\")\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 15. Overfit / underfit check \u2014 Stage 2\n",
    "\n",
    "Same idea as Example 1/2 in class: compute the metrics on train data too, then compare."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "reg_train_pred = reg_pipeline.predict(X_train)\n",
    "\n",
    "regression_metrics(y_reg_train, reg_train_pred, label=\"Training Data\")\n",
    "print()\n",
    "regression_metrics(y_reg_test, reg_test_pred, label=\"Test Data\")\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**My interpretation:** *(fill this in after running on your real data \u2014 compare train vs test\n",
    "RMSE/R\u00b2 and say whether the model is overfitting, underfitting, or a good fit, using the table\n",
    "from the slides: R\u00b2 0.9-1.0 excellent, 0.7-0.9 good, 0.5-0.7 moderate, below 0.5 weak.)*"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "# 16. Try the two models on a few test rows\n",
    "\n",
    "Same idea as the \"Predict new instances\" example from class just instead of typing a brand new\n",
    "row by hand, we run both pipelines on a handful of real test rows and put the results side by\n",
    "side."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "sample = X_test.head(10).copy()\n",
    "\n",
    "sample_class_pred = clf_pipeline.predict(sample)\n",
    "sample_reg_pred   = reg_pipeline.predict(sample)\n",
    "\n",
    "results = pd.DataFrame({\n",
    "    \"actual_delayed_15\":   y_class_test.loc[sample.index].values,\n",
    "    \"predicted_delayed_15\": sample_class_pred,\n",
    "    \"actual_delay_minutes\": y_reg_test.loc[sample.index].round(1).values,\n",
    "    \"predicted_delay_minutes\": np.round(sample_reg_pred, 1),\n",
    "})\n",
    "\n",
    "results\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "# Conclusion\n",
    "\n",
    "This simplified notebook keeps the same two-stage idea predict *whether* a delay happens\n",
    "(Logistic Regression), then predict *how long* it is (Linear Regression) but only uses\n",
    "techniques covered in the course:\n",
    "\n",
    "- Random 80/20 `train_test_split`\n",
    "- A `ColumnTransformer` with `SimpleImputer` + `StandardScaler` (numeric) and\n",
    "  `SimpleImputer` + `OneHotEncoder` (categorical), shared by both models\n",
    "- `LogisticRegression` and `LinearRegression` from `sklearn.linear_model`\n",
    "- Standard evaluation metrics from class: Accuracy / Precision / Recall / F1 / Confusion\n",
    "  Matrix for Stage 1, and MAE / MSE / RMSE / R\u00b2 for Stage 2\n",
    "- Overfit/underfit checked the way we were taught: compare train vs test metrics\n",
    "\n",
    "*(Replace this paragraph with your own 2-3 sentence summary once you've run the notebook on\n",
    "your real data fill in your actual accuracy/F1/RMSE/R\u00b2 numbers and say what they mean.)*"
   ]
  }
 ],
